Documentation.name: NMM
Documentation.notes: NATO Architecture Framework Metamodel

Stereotype.name: ActivityComposition
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that the parent activity has the child as a part - i.e. the child activity is conducted as part of conducting the parent activity.Note: Unfortunately, UML offers two ways to do this; by composite class properties (i.e. this stereotype) and by UML::CallBehaviourAction. To prevent ambiguity, this meta-model forces both approaches to be used in parallel (SysML takes the same approach). Any ActivityComposition must be accompanied by a corresponding OperationalActivityAction. Hopefully, a future version of UML may be more coherent in this department, and this duplication can be removed.

Stereotype.name: ActivityMapsToCapability
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a StandardOperationalActivity is in some way part of a capability.The nature of the mapping should be specified in the name of the dependency.

Stereotype.name: ActivitySubject
Stereotype.notes: Anything that is acted upon by an OperationalActivity

Stereotype.name: ActivityToFunctionMapping
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a Function (at least in part) performs or assists in the conducting of an OperationalActivity.

Stereotype.name: ActsUpon
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that something (subject) is acted upon by an OperationalActivity (activity).

Stereotype.name: ActualCompetence
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an <<ActualOrganizationalResource>> actually has a <<Competence>>

Stereotype.name: ActualLocation
Stereotype.notes: A location anywhere on the earth. The means of describing the location is a string (locationDescription). The information contained in that string is governed by the taxonomy reference - e.g. if the ActualLocation is a “GPS reference”, the string will contain the GPS coordinates.

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganization
Stereotype.notes: An actual specific organization, an instance of an organization class - e.g. "The US Department of Defense"

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganizationComposition
Stereotype.notes: Relates an actual specific organization to an actual specific organizational resource that fulfils a role in that organization.

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganizationRelationship
Stereotype.notes: A relationship between two actual specific organizations or parts of an organization.Note1: the <<TypicalOrganizationRelationship>> which is realized by the <<ActualOrganizationRelationship>> is referred to via the typicalRelationship attribute.

Tag.name: typicalRelationship
Tag.description: Refers to the TypicalOrganizationRelationship which is realised by the ActualOrganizationRelationship. This attribute is optional - i.e. ActualOrganizationRelationships may be created ad-hoc with no reference to a TypicalOrganizationRelationship.

Stereotype.name: ActualOrganizationalResource
Stereotype.notes: An instance of either an actual organization or an actual post. [ABSTRACT]

Stereotype.name: ActualPost
Stereotype.notes: An actual, specific post, an instance of a PostType class - e.g. "President of the United States of America"

Stereotype.name: Alias
Stereotype.notes: An alternative name for an element.

Tag.name: nameOwner
Tag.description: The person or organization that uses this alternative name

Stereotype.name: ArbitraryConnection
Stereotype.notes: Represents a visual indication of connection used in high level operational concept diagrams. The connections are purely indicative and cannot be related to any architectural semantics.

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalDescription
Stereotype.notes: A specification of a system of systems at a technical level which also provides the business context for the system of systems.IEEE1471 describes an architectural description as "a collection of products to document the architecture of a system". This is something of a circular definition (as product in this sense is an architectural product), and also assumes a technical system, whereas architectures complying with this meta-model describe an enterprise - i.e. the system of systems and the human processes they support.

Tag.name: dateCompleted
Tag.description: A date conforming to the ISO8601 date-time format - see also <<>>

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalFramework
Stereotype.notes: A set of connected View specifications which serve to define how an Enterprise may be represented by an ArchitecturalDescription

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalProduct
Stereotype.notes: A connected and coherent set of Architectural Elements which conform to a View.

Tag.name: architecturalElements
Tag.description: Represents all the architectural elements that constitute the product.

Tag.name: description
Tag.description: Represents a short description of the product.

Stereotype.name: ArchitecturalReference
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one architectural description (referrer) refers to another (referred).

Stereotype.name: Architecture
Stereotype.notes: An abstraction of an Enterprise, represented by an ArchitecturalDescription

Stereotype.name: ArchitectureMetaData
Stereotype.notes: A Metadata element that applies to the whole architecture.

Stereotype.name: AssignedProperty
Stereotype.notes: A property with a value assigned.

Stereotype.name: AsynchronousMessage
Stereotype.notes: A signal which is transmitted irregularly with respect to time.Note: An asynchronous message is not guaranteed to arrive in a specific time following a request.

Stereotype.name: Attribute
Stereotype.notes: A defined property of an Entity.

Stereotype.name: BehaviouralModel
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that specifies the behaviour of the enterprise or part of the enterprise.

Stereotype.name: Capability
Stereotype.notes: A high level specification of the enterprise's ability

Stereotype.name: CapabilityComposition
Stereotype.notes: A parent-child relationship between two capabilities - i.e. the relationship indicates one capability (child) is a sub-capability of the other (parent). Note for MOD Users: Although the MOD tends to work in terms of capabilities and capability functions, it is not always apparent that there is any difference between them other than their relative positions in a capability taxonomy, which is specified by the <<CapabilityComposition>> relationship.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: A combination of organizational aspects (with their competencies) and equipment that combine to provide a capability. A <<CapabilityConfiguration>> is a physical asset or organization configured to provide a capability, and must be guided by [doctrine] which may take the form of <<Standard>> or <<OperationalConstraint>> stereotypes. Edited MANP 08.03.13: 7 new Attributes

Stereotype.name: CapabilityDependency
Stereotype.notes: A relationship which asserts that a capability (toCapability) is dependent on another (fromCapability) capability in the context of an overall capability.Note: this dependency relates parts (i.e. properties) in a composite class diagram, therefore each dependency is in context of the parent composite class.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityForNode
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a Node is required to have a Capability to the level specified by a CapabilityRequirement

Tag.name: context
Tag.description: If a capability is required only for one specific usage of a node (i.e. <<NodeAssemblyUsage>> then this attribute points at the property.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityIncrement
Stereotype.notes: A ProjectMilestone that indicates the point in time at which a project is predicted to deliver or has delivered a CapabilityRequirement.Example: When a project reaches Initial Operating Capability (IOC) it may deliver a CapabilityRequirement with a given set of metrics then deliver a second CapabilityRequirement corresponding to the same Capability when it reaches Full Operational Capability (FOC). Both the IOC and FOC milestones would be instances of CapabilityIncrement

Stereotype.name: CapabilityRealisation
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a CapabilityConfiguration is capable of achieving a Capability (preferably a MeasuredCapability)

Stereotype.name: CapabilitySpecialisation
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one Capability is a special case of the other.

Stereotype.name: Climate
Stereotype.notes: A type of weather condition, or combination of weather conditions (e.g. high temperature & dry).

Stereotype.name: Competence
Stereotype.notes: A specific set of abilities defined by knowledge, skills and attitude.

Stereotype.name: CompetenceForRole
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an Role requires a Competence.

Stereotype.name: CompositeStructureModel
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that specifies the structural aspects of the enterprise or part of the enterprise.

Stereotype.name: ConceptDescription
Stereotype.notes: A textual representation of a HighLevelOperationalConcept

Stereotype.name: Concern
Stereotype.notes: An interest in a subject held by one or more stakeholder <<OrganizationalResource>>.

Stereotype.name: ConfigurationDeployed
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an <<ActualOrganizationResource>> started to use, or is slated to start using a <<CapabilityConfiguration>> from a specific point in time.This is used to describe capabilities going into service with specific organizations or posts.

Stereotype.name: ConfigurationNoLongerUsed
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an <<ActualOrganizationResource>> ceased to use or is slated to cease using a <<CapabilityConfiguration>> from a specific point in time.This is used to describe capabilities going out of service with specific organizations or posts.

Stereotype.name: ConformsTo
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an element in the architecture conforms to a Standard

Stereotype.name: ConnectionProperties
Stereotype.notes: A collection of properties with assigned values. An element with this stereotype has attributes stereotyped using AssignedProperties.

Stereotype.name: ControlFlow
Stereotype.notes: CH Extension to add Control Flows in Activity diagrams

Stereotype.name: DataElement
Stereotype.notes: A formalised representation of data which is managed by or exchanged between systems.

Tag.name: PrivacyProtection
Tag.values: no personal data,personal data,sensitive personal data,personality profile,danger of life and limb

Stereotype.name: DataEntity
Stereotype.notes: A definition (type) of an item of interest.

Stereotype.name: DataModel
Stereotype.notes: A structural specification of data, showing classifications of data elements and relationships between them. [ABSTRACT]

Stereotype.name: DefinedByEntity
Stereotype.notes: A relation that shows that a DataElement is defined by a DataEntity. (An extension to NAF, introduced to emphasize relationships between DataElements and DataEntities.)

Stereotype.name: Definition
Stereotype.notes: A definition of an element in the architecture. Note - every element added by an architect must have a definition.

Stereotype.name: EnduringTask
Stereotype.notes: A type of behaviour recognised by an enterprise as being essential to achieving its goals - i.e. a strategic specification of what the enterprise does.

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseGoal
Stereotype.notes: A specific, required objective of the enterprise that the architecture represents.Note: Benefits of achieving the goal are presented as a list of textual items.

Stereotype.name: EnterprisePhase
Stereotype.notes: A current or future state of a WholeLifeEnterprise or another EnterprisePhase.

Tag.name: toBe
Tag.description: Asserts if the EnterprisePhase specified is an aspirational (i.e future) state of the enterprise. Although this can be deduced from the "from" and "to" attributes at the time the architecture is produced, that will not be immediately apparent for users viewing the architecture in the future (i.e. once the "from" date has passed)

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseStructure
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one EnterprisePhase is a spatial part of another.Note: This is a topological structuring relationship, hence the EnterprisePhase may be physically disjoint

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseTemporalPart
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one EnterprisePhase is a temporal part of another.Note: This means that both EnterprisePhases have the same spatial extent - i..e this is only a temporal structure.

Stereotype.name: EnterpriseVision
Stereotype.notes: The overall aims of an enterprise over a given period of time.

Stereotype.name: EntityRelationship
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that there is a relationship between two entities.

Stereotype.name: Environment
Stereotype.notes: A definition of the conditions in which the Enterprise exists or functions. An Environment may be specified in terms of LocationType (e.g. terrain), WeatherCondition (e.g. cloud, rain, etc.) and Climate (e.g. tropical), and LightCondition (e.g. dark, light, dusk, etc.)

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentalConditions
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a Capability's capabilityMetric (MeasureableProperty) is valid for a particular environment.Example - a capability with a rate of advance of 40 km per day must be qualified by the environment for which this is specified - e.g. desert conditions.

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentalProperty
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an Environment has one or more properties. These may be Climate, LocationType, or LightCondition.

Stereotype.name: ExternalIndividual
Stereotype.notes: An individual (i.e. something which has spatial and temporal extent) defined by an external ontology.

Stereotype.name: ExternalType
Stereotype.notes: A type defined by an external ontology.Note: this may be higher-order - i.e. a type of a type

Stereotype.name: FieldedCapability
Stereotype.notes: An actual, fully-realised capability. A FieldedCapability must indicate its configuration CapabilityConfiguration.Example: "HMS Iron Duke, configured and crewed, operating under the appropriate doctrine". Note - the CapabilityConfiguration that this realises would specify a UK Type 23 Frigate, the crew, the weapons systems, etc.

Stereotype.name: Forecast
Stereotype.notes: A statement about the future state of one or more types of system or standard.Note, this is an EffectivityConstrainedItem - i.e. the forecast is effective for a given period.

Stereotype.name: FrequencyRange
Stereotype.notes: A MeasureableProperty that specifies maximum and minimum frequencies, measured in Hertz as real numbers.

Stereotype.name: Function
Stereotype.notes: An activity which is specified in context of the resource (human or machine) that performs it.Note1: Contrast with OperationalActivity, where the actor performing the activity is not known (i.e. it is just a logical node). A Function is implementation-specific.Note2: Should the Function be specific to one usage of a type of system, then the usageContext is specified by a reference to the composite structure property ResourceComposition typed by the system.

Stereotype.name: FunctionComposition
Stereotype.notes: Integration of NAF3.1 Composition

Stereotype.name: FunctionFlow
Stereotype.notes: An UML::ObjectFlow between Functions.

Stereotype.name: FunctionProvision
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a FunctionalResource provides a Function.

Stereotype.name: FunctionalResource
Stereotype.notes: A <<Resource>> capable of function. Note that <<PhysicalAsset>> and OrganizationalResource (<<PostType>>, <<OrganizationType>> are not considered to be <<FunctionalResource>>s.

Stereotype.name: FunctionsUpon
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a SystemFunction has some effect on an DataElement

Stereotype.name: HighLevelOperationalConcept
Stereotype.notes: A generalized model for operations.Note: a background image may be associated with the HLOC, which is referred to by the backgroundImageURL attribute. Scaling information is also provided about the image, so that when an ItemInConcept is shown in the diagram, it can be properly located and scaled. No units are specified, but the same length unit shall be used throughout a single OV-1a product.

Tag.name: backgroundImageSizeX
Tag.description: The width of the background image. No units are specified, but the same units must also be used in <<ItemInConcept>>. If the image reference by the backgroundImageURL is wider than specified here, the image shall be scaled to meet this dimension.

Tag.name: backgroundImageSizeY
Tag.description: The height of the background image. No units are specified, but the same units must also be used in <<ItemInConcept>>. If the image reference by the backgroundImageURL is higher than specified here, the image shall be scaled to meet this dimension.

Tag.name: backgroundImageURL
Tag.description: A URL reference to the background image file used in presenting the OV-1

Stereotype.name: ISO8601DateTime
Stereotype.notes: A date and time specified in the ISO8601 date-time format including timezone designator (TZD): YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssTZD So, 7:20pm and 30 seconds on 30th July 2005 in the CET timezone would be represented as "2005-07-30T19:20:30+01:00". The date time string is represented by the value attribute of UML::LiteralString.

Stereotype.name: ImplementsProtocol
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a ProtocolImplementation implements a Protocol

Stereotype.name: InformationElement
Stereotype.notes: A formalized representation of information subject to an operational process.

Stereotype.name: InformationExchange
Stereotype.notes: A specification of the information that is to be exchanged. An InformationExchange must have a unique identifier.Note: additional information about the requirements for the InformationExchange may be provided by the requirementText attribute

Tag.name: identifier
Tag.description: the unique identifier of the InformationExchange

Stereotype.name: InformationExchangeMessage
Stereotype.notes: A message representing the exchange of information defined by an InformationExchange

Stereotype.name: InformationModel
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that represents the structure of information - e.g. a logical or physical data model.

Stereotype.name: ItemInConcept
Stereotype.notes: A relationship which asserts that a ConceptItem forms part of the high level operational concept .

Tag.name: iconHeight
Tag.description: The height of the icon. Units are not specified, but shall be the same as those used in the <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>. If the icon referenced by the iconURL is higher then this specified value, the icon shall be scaled to this height.

Tag.name: iconPositionX
Tag.description: The position of the centre of the icon relative to the lefthand side of the backgroundImage of the <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>. Units are not specified, but shall be the same as those used inthe <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>.

Tag.name: iconURL
Tag.description: A URL referring to an image that is used to represent the ConceptItem in the OV-1 product.

Tag.name: iconWidth
Tag.description: The width of the icon. Units are not specified, but shall be the same as those used in the <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>.If the icon referenced by the iconURL is wider then this specified value, the icon shall be scaled to this width.

Tag.name: iconPositionY
Tag.description: The position of the centre of the icon relative to the bottom of the backgroundImage of the <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>. Units are not specified, but shall be the same as those used inthe <<HighLevelOperationalConcept>>.

Stereotype.name: LightCondition
Stereotype.notes: A specification of environmental lighting conditions. Examples would be daylight, dusk, night, moonlight, artificial

Stereotype.name: LocationType
Stereotype.notes: A general specification of the surroundings / scenario in which an operation may take place. Examples would be: "desert", "arctic", "at sea", etc.

Stereotype.name: LogicalDataModel
Stereotype.notes: A LogicalDataModel is a specification of business information requirements as a formal data structure, where relationships and classes (entities) are used to specify the logic which underpins the information.

Stereotype.name: Matrix
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that presents information in a tabular form.

Stereotype.name: MeasurableProperty
Stereotype.notes: An AssignedProperty of something in the physical world, expressed in amounts of a unit of measure. The property may have a required value - either specified by the [defaultValue] from uml::property attribute, or the [minValue] and [maxValue] to specify a required range.

Stereotype.name: MessageHandler
Stereotype.notes: An aspect of a <<ServiceInterfaceDefinition>> which receives incoming <<AsynchronousMessage>>s

Stereotype.name: MetaData
Stereotype.notes: Annotation that can be applied to any element in the architecture.Note: wherever possible, standard Meta-Data types should be used - e.g. conforming to Dublin CoreNote for MOD Users: The MOD Meta Data Standard categories shall be used.

Tag.name: name
Tag.description: Represents the name of the Meta-Data element - e.g. "title", "version number"

Tag.name: dublinCoreElement
Tag.description: If the meta data corresponds to the Dublin Core Meta-Data Standard, then the meta-data element name should be listed here

Tag.name: modMetaDataElement
Tag.description: If the meta data corresponds to the MOD Meta-Data Standard, then the meta-data element name should be listed here

Stereotype.name: MilestoneInProject
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a ProjectMilestone belongs to a project. A milestone shall not belong to more than one project.

Stereotype.name: MilestoneRelationship
Stereotype.notes: A relationship between two milestones.

Stereotype.name: Mission
Stereotype.notes: A purpose to which a person, organization or autonomous system is tasked

Stereotype.name: Needline
Stereotype.notes: A relationship specifying the need to exchange information between nodes, uniquely identified in context of the OV-2 product by its needlineNumber.Note: The needline does not indicate how the transfer is implemented.

Tag.name: needlineNumber
Tag.description: The unique (in context of the given OV-2 product) identifier for the needline

Stereotype.name: Node
Stereotype.notes: A logical entity that performs operational activities. Note: nodes are specified independently of any physical realisation.

Stereotype.name: NodeAssemblyUsage
Stereotype.notes: Used to link a parent Node to its sub-nodes. Note: Only NodeAssemblyUsage may be used to represent a node-subnode relationship.

Stereotype.name: NodeConnectionEnd
Stereotype.notes: The end of a connector between nodes - i.e. for Needline and NodeConnector.

Stereotype.name: NodeConnector
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a physical flow exists or is required between Nodes (e.g. flows of people, materiel, or energy).

Stereotype.name: NodeEnvironment
Stereotype.notes: A specification of the Environment in which the node operates or is required to operate.

Stereotype.name: NodeHasBehaviour
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an OperationalActivity is conducted at a Node. Should the same type of node be used in different contexts in the architecture, and the activity is conducted under only one of the contexts, that context is provided by the [nodeUsageContext] property.

Stereotype.name: NodeInProblemDomain
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a Node is within a ProblemDomain

Stereotype.name: NodeRealisation
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a CapabilityConfiguration provides the functionality specified by an operational node.

Stereotype.name: NodeRelationshipDescription
Stereotype.notes: A CompositeStructureModel whose parts are either Nodes or ProblemDomainss

Stereotype.name: Ontology
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that represents real-world individuals and classes, and the relationships between them.

Stereotype.name: OpActivityInputPin
Stereotype.notes: A port for flows that feed into an activity.

Tag.name: isControl
Tag.description: Asserts if the input pin plays the tole of a control input (as used in some activity modelling languages such as IDEF0)

Tag.name: isMechanism
Tag.description: Asserts if the input pin plays the tole of a mechanism input (as used in some activity modelling languages such as IDEF0)

Stereotype.name: OpActivityOutputPin
Stereotype.notes: A port for flows that leave an activity.

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivity
Stereotype.notes: A logical process, specified independently of how the process is carried out. Note: an OperationalActivity may only be carried out by a logical Node.

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivityAction
Stereotype.notes: Used to relate an OperationalActivity to its sub-activities. Note1: An OperationalActivityAction will be created for every OperationalActivity to provide a way to manage sub-activities, and to allow flows between activities.Note2: See also ActivityCompositionNote3: Also provides a means for attaching information (properties) to an activity.

Stereotype.name: OperationalActivityFlow
Stereotype.notes: A flow of information, energy or materiel from one activity to another.

Stereotype.name: OperationalConstraint
Stereotype.notes: A rule governing an operational behaviour or property.

Tag.name: nodeUsageContext
Tag.description: In cases where a constraint applies only to a specific usage of a node (in a composite class diagram), this attribute should be set to point at the property that represents this usage.

Stereotype.name: OperationalInteractionSpecification
Stereotype.notes: A specification of the interactions between nodes in an operational architecture.

Stereotype.name: OperationalNodeLifeline
Stereotype.notes: A lifeline which represents a usage of a node in an operational architecture.

Tag.name: nodeUsageContext
Tag.description: In the case where the subject of the lifeline is a Node, it may be necessary to distinguish which useage of the node type is being referred to. If the context is a node and nodeUsageContext is unset (nil) then the behaviour defined by the state machine is assumed to apply to all usages of that type of node.

Stereotype.name: OperationalStateDescription
Stereotype.notes: A rule governing an operational behaviour or property.

Tag.name: nodeUsageContext
Tag.description: In the case where the context of the state machine is a Node, it may be necessary to distinguish which useage of the node type is being referred to. If the context is a node and nodeUsageContext is unset (nil) then the behaviour defined by the state machine is assumed to apply to all usages of that type of node.

Stereotype.name: OperationalSwimlane
Stereotype.notes: A visual representation of nodes which conduct activities, shown as "swimlanes".

Stereotype.name: OrgResourceReference
Stereotype.notes: A reference to an <<ActualPost>> or <<ActualOrganization>>

Stereotype.name: OrganizationProjectRelationship
Stereotype.notes: A relationship between an <<ActualOrganization>> and a <<Project>>.Example: ownershipExample: supplier

Stereotype.name: OrganizationType
Stereotype.notes: A group of persons, associated for a particular purpose.

Stereotype.name: OrganizationalResource
Stereotype.notes: Either an organization, or a post. [ABSTRACT]

Stereotype.name: OutOfService
Stereotype.notes: A ProjectMilestone that indicates a project's deliverable is to go out of service.

Stereotype.name: PhysicalAsset
Stereotype.notes: A <<Resource>> that can host systems and/or people. Note 1: synonyms for <<PhysicalAsset>>; would be "platform", "facility", or "host". This is the original intent for the "SystemsNode" concept in DoDAF.Note 2: A <<PhysicalAsset>> can contribute to a <<CapabilityConfiguration>>, and is usually configured for that purpose. It may be that a given platform can be configured and manned in many different ways to achieve different capabilities. In these cases, a class should be created for the <<PhysicalAsset>> in general, and this should be abstract. The variants of the asset should be created as concrete classes, specialising from the abstract class. Edited MANP 08.03.13: 7 new Attributes

Stereotype.name: PhysicalDataModel
Stereotype.notes: A PhysicalDataModel is an implementable specification of a data structure. A PhysicalDataModelrealises a LogicalDataModel, taking into account implementation restrictions and performance issues whilststill enforcing the constraints, relationships and typing of the logical model.

Stereotype.name: PortType
Stereotype.notes: A type of System which is used to provide an interface to which other systems connect. A PortType may be implemented as a SystemPort.

Stereotype.name: PostType
Stereotype.notes: A type of point of contact or responsible person. Note that this is the type of post - e.g. Desk Officer, Commander Land Component, etc.

Stereotype.name: ProblemDomain
Stereotype.notes: The boundary containing those Nodes which may be realised by functional resources specified in SV-1. There may be more than one alternative solution for a given ProblemDomain specified as a set of SV suites.

Stereotype.name: ProcessOwner
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an OrganizationalResource has responsibility for an OperationalActivity. Note this does not imply the resource conducts the activity, merely that it has managerial responsibility for it.

Stereotype.name: ProductOfView
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that an ArchitecturalProduct conforms to a View specification

Stereotype.name: Project
Stereotype.notes: A time-limited endeavour to create a specific set of products or services.

Stereotype.name: ProjectMilestone
Stereotype.notes: An event in a Project by which progress is measured - modelled as a Project of zero duration.Note: in the case of an acquisition project, there are two key types of milestone which shall be represented using subtypes - CapabilityIncrement and OutOfService

Stereotype.name: ProjectOwnership
Stereotype.notes: A type of <<OrganizationProjectRelationship>> where the organization is the party responsible for the project.

Stereotype.name: ProjectSequence
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one Project follows from another - i.e. the target Project cannot start until the source Project has ended

Stereotype.name: ProjectTheme
Stereotype.notes: An aspect by which the progress of various Projects may be measured.In UK MOD, this could be one of the defence lines of development, or DOTMLPF in the US.

Stereotype.name: ProjectType
Stereotype.notes: A category of ProjectExample: "Programme"Example: "Acquisition Project"Example: "Training Programme"

Stereotype.name: ProjectWholePart
Stereotype.notes: Relates a parent project (owningProject) to a sub-project (relatedProject).

Stereotype.name: Protocol
Stereotype.notes: A Standard for communication. Protocols may be composite (i.e. a stack).

Stereotype.name: ProtocolStack
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a Protocol (upperLayer) uses another Protocol (lowerLayer)

Stereotype.name: QualitativeProperty
Stereotype.notes: An AssignedProperty whose value is a text literal (string).

Stereotype.name: RadioFrequencyPort
Stereotype.notes: A PortType which uses radio frequency as its mode of communication.

Tag.name: frequencyUsage
Tag.description: The minimum operating frequency supported by the port type, measure in Hertz.

Stereotype.name: RadioFrequencyPortConnector
Stereotype.notes: A SystemPortConnector that connects two ports which are typed as RadioFrequencyPort.

Stereotype.name: RatificationBody
Stereotype.notes: Asserts than an <<ActualOrganization>> is responsible for the ratification of a standard.

Stereotype.name: ReferredLocation
Stereotype.notes: Either an actual location, or a type of location (i.e. environment) at/in which operations may be conducted. [ABSTRACT]

Stereotype.name: RelatedProjectReference
Stereotype.notes: A reference to a sub-project from a ProjectWholePart relationship.

Stereotype.name: RepresentedByEntity
Stereotype.notes: A relation that shows that an InformationElement is represented by a DataEntity. (An extension to NAF, introduced to emphasize relationships between InformationElements and DataEntities.)

Stereotype.name: RequiredNodeLocation
Stereotype.notes: Relates a node to a location to assert that the operational node is required to be situated at that location.

Stereotype.name: Resource
Stereotype.notes: A <<PhysicalAsset>>, <<OrganizationalResource>> or FunctionalResource that can contribute towards fulfilling a capability [ABSTRACT]

Tag.name: PrivacyProtection
Tag.values: no personal data,personal data,sensitive personal data,personality profile,danger of life and limb

Stereotype.name: ResourceComposition
Stereotype.notes: A relationship between <<Resources>> that asserts one resource is part of the other (i.e. composition).NOTE: Valid Resource combinations are:* PhysicalAsset(whole) - System(part) - i.e. a system being hosted on an asset* PhysicalAsset(whole) - PhysicalAsset(part) - i.e. one asset being a physical part of the other* PhysicalAsset(whole) - Role(part) - i.e. a person or organization being hosted on an asset (e.g. a ship, deployed HQ facility, etc.)* CapabilityConfiguration(whole) - PhysicalAsset(part) - i.e. a physical asset being the main platform for achievement of a capability* CapabilityConfiguration(whole) - Role(part) - i.e. a person or organization being the basis for capability achievement* CapabilityConfiguration(whole) - CapabilityConfiguration(part) - i.e. a capability being achieved by the assembly of multiple CapabilityConfigurations

Stereotype.name: ResourceConstraint
Stereotype.notes: A rule governing the structural or functional aspects of an implementation - this may also include constraints on <<OrganizationalResource>>s that are part of an implementation

Stereotype.name: ResourceInteraction
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that two FunctionalResources interact.Examples: data exchange between systems, conversations between people, people using systems

Stereotype.name: ResourceInteractionSpecification
Stereotype.notes: A specification of the interactions between aspects of a Resources architecture.

Stereotype.name: ResourceLifeLine
Stereotype.notes: A UML::Lifeline that represents a ResourceLifelineItem that interacts with another ResourceLifelineItem

Stereotype.name: ResourcePartition
Stereotype.notes: A swimlane representing a usage of a FunctionalResource.

Stereotype.name: ResourceStateMachine
Stereotype.notes: A state transition model which represents the behaviour of a Resource or Function.

Stereotype.name: ResourceStructureModel
Stereotype.notes: A CompositeStructureModel that is the container for resources and their interactions.

Stereotype.name: Role
Stereotype.notes: An aspect of a person or organization that enables them to fulfil a particular function.

Stereotype.name: SameAs
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that two elements refer to the same real-world thing

Stereotype.name: Service
Stereotype.notes: A type of delivered functionality, specified independently of the capabilities that provide it.Note: A service may or may not have a physical effect on its environmentOASIS Definition: A service is a mechanism to enable access to a set of one or more capabilities, where the access is provided using a prescribed interface and is exercised consistent with constraints and policies as specified by the service description.

Stereotype.name: ServiceAimsToAchieve
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a Service is intended to deliver a CapabilityNote: multiple instantiations of this element may be required, as it is likely that more than one service is required to achieve a capability.

Stereotype.name: ServiceAttribute
Stereotype.notes: A property of Service.Example: availability

Stereotype.name: ServiceComposition
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a Service (parentService) calls upon another Service (childService) in order to deliver its stated functionality.

Stereotype.name: ServiceConnectorEnd
Stereotype.notes: One of two ends of a ServiceNeedline

Stereotype.name: ServiceConsumer
Stereotype.notes: A UML::Actor representing an unknown service user.

Stereotype.name: ServiceFunction
Stereotype.notes: A type of activity describing the functionality of a service

Stereotype.name: ServiceGeneralisation
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that one Service class is a specialisation of another.

Stereotype.name: ServiceInteractionSpecification
Stereotype.notes: A model representing how a set of Service classes interacts with one another.

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterface
Stereotype.notes: The mechanism by which a <<Service>> communicates.Note: a <<ServiceInterface>> specifies the <<ServiceInterfaceDefinition>> provided and required by the <<Service>>

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceDefinition
Stereotype.notes: The specification of a provided or required communication method exposed by a ServiceInterface

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceOperation
Stereotype.notes: A function or procedure which enables programmatic communication with a <<Service>> via a <<ServiceInterface>>

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceParameter
Stereotype.notes: A constant or variable passed into or out of a ServiceInterface as part of the execution of a ServiceInterfaceOperation

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceSchema
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a PhysicalDataModel defines the data structure used by a ServiceInterface when communicating with a Service or client.

Stereotype.name: ServiceLevel
Stereotype.notes: A value specification for a set of ServiceAttributes indicating the level to which a CapabilityConfiguration delivers a ServiceExample: A ServiceAttribute "availability" may be defined against a Service. A given CapabilityConfiguration could have a corresponding ServiceLevel - e.g. "90%"

Tag.name: locationType
Tag.description: Shall be a <<LocationType>> stereotype

Stereotype.name: ServiceLifeLine
Stereotype.notes: A part of a ServiceInteractionSpecification denoting the role of a ServiceInterface.

Stereotype.name: ServiceNeedline
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that two Services need to communicate when assembled together under another Service

Stereotype.name: ServicePolicy
Stereotype.notes: A constraint governing one or more Services

Stereotype.name: ServiceProvision
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a CapabilityConfiguration delivers a Service to a specified ServiceLevel

Stereotype.name: ServiceStateMachine
Stereotype.notes: A model representing the changes of state which are possible for a Service

Stereotype.name: ServiceSupportsActivity
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a Service in some way contributes or assists in the execution of an OperationalActivity

Stereotype.name: SpectrumAllocation
Stereotype.notes: A Standard specifying a particular frequency range of the electromagnetic spectrum that is allotted to a particular usage.

Tag.name: usage
Tag.description: A description of the alloted usage for the frequency range

Stereotype.name: StakeholderHasConcern
Stereotype.notes: An assertion that a Stakeholder has a Concern

Stereotype.name: Standard
Stereotype.notes: A ratified and peer-reviewed specification that is used to guide or constrain the architecture. A Standard may be applied to any element in the architecture via the [constrainedItem] property of UML::Constraint.

Tag.name: identifier
Tag.description: Represents the number or name of the standard that uniquely identifies it.

Tag.name: publishedWebsite
Tag.description: Represents the URL of the website where the standard may be found (if published online) or the website of the publisher if the standard is only available to purchase.

Tag.name: publisher
Tag.description: Represents the name of the publisher - e.g. "ISO", "BSI", "IEEE", "OMG", etc.

Tag.name: ratificationDate
Tag.description: The date when this version of the standard was published. Shall be a &lt&ltISO8601DateTime&gt&gt stereotype.

Tag.name: version
Tag.description: Represents the revision number of the standard - e.g. "1.2.1", "v2", ":2004", etc.

Tag.name: withdrawalDate
Tag.description: Shall be a &lt&ltISO8601DateTime&gt&gt stereotype.

Stereotype.name: StandardConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: A UML::Comment that when attached to a CapabilityConfiguration indicates that it is a standard pattern for re-use in the architecture.

Stereotype.name: StandardOperationalActivity
Stereotype.notes: An <<OperationalActivity>> that is a standard procedure that is doctrinal .Note: This is equivalent to what some defense organizations call JETLs

Stereotype.name: Status
Stereotype.notes: An allowable value for a StatusIndicatorExample - 3Example - amber

Stereotype.name: StatusAtMilestone
Stereotype.notes: A relationship between a Status and a milestone which asserts the status (i.e. level of progress) of a ProjectTheme for the project at the time of the milestone.For example, a procurement project may have workstreams corresponding to lines of development. The status of each of workstream is summarised on the milestone in the AcV-2.

Stereotype.name: StatusIndicators
Stereotype.notes: An enumeration of the possible statuses for one or more ProjectThemes.Example - 1 to 5Example - red, amber, green

Stereotype.name: StatusLiteral
Stereotype.notes: A literal value corresponding to a Status

Stereotype.name: StereotypeExtension
Stereotype.notes: Defines an additional stereotype used in the architecture which is not defined in this meta-model. The body attribute contains the name of the new stereotype. The extendedStereotype tagged value shall contain the name of the meta-model stereotype which is extended. The ontologyReference tagged value shall be populated with a reference to the external ontology element represented by the new stereotype.Note: this is effectively a short-hand method for representing ontology items in the architecture. New stereotype names can be created at will by the architect, provided that they reference an element in a recognised external ontology.Note: Any stereotypes added by the architect which do not have a corresponding StereotypeExtension will be deemed non-compliant and ignored by tools importing data compliant to this meta-model.

Stereotype.name: SubtypeRelationship
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that one Entity (subtype) is a specialization of the other (supertype).

Stereotype.name: System
Stereotype.notes: A coherent combination of physical artefacts, energy and information, assembled for a purpose.Edited MANP 08.03.13: 7 new Attributes

Stereotype.name: SystemPort
Stereotype.notes: An interface (logical or physical) provided by a <<System>>. A <<SystemPort>> may implement a <<PortType>>, though there is no requirement for <<SystemPort>>s to be typed.

Stereotype.name: SystemPortConnector
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a connection exists between two ports belonging to parts in a system composite structure model.

Stereotype.name: SystemPortConnectorEnd
Stereotype.notes: The end of a connector between system ports.

Stereotype.name: SystemStructureModel
Stereotype.notes: A CompositeStructureModel whose parts are Systems

Stereotype.name: TextProduct
Stereotype.notes: An ArchitecturalProduct that is represented as text.

Stereotype.name: VersionOfConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: Asserts that a CapabilityConfiguration is a version of a WholeLifeConfiguration.

Stereotype.name: View
Stereotype.notes: A specification of a way to present an aspect of the architecture. Views are defined with one or more purposes in mind - e.g. showing the logical topology of the enterprise, describing a process model, defining a data model, etc.

Tag.name: viewCode
Tag.description: Represents the short-hand code used for the view (if one is used) - e.g. "SV-6a"

Tag.name: viewName
Tag.description: Represents the name of the view - e.g. "Operational Node Connectivity Diagram"

Tag.name: viewDescription
Tag.description: Represents a short description of the view, outlining the types of element typically found in that view.

Tag.name: framework
Tag.description: Represents the name of the architectural framework which defined the view

Tag.name: frameworkWebsite
Tag.description: Represents a reference to the URL of the website where the framework is described - e.g. www.modaf.com

Stereotype.name: VisionStatement
Stereotype.notes: A high-level textual description of a CapabilityVision.Note: VisionStatement is a stereotype of UML::Comment and the [body] of the comment shall be represented as XHTML. If plain text is required, then no HMTL tags should be embedded.

Stereotype.name: WholeLifeConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: A set of versions of a Capability Configuration over time.WholeLifeConfiguration is used to collect together successive versions of CapabilityConfiguraitons from the first design to the last.

Stereotype.name: WholeLifeEnterprise
Stereotype.notes: An EnterprisePhase that represents the whole existance of an enterprise.

TaggedValueType.description: Asserts that an <<ActualOrganisationRelationship>> is an instance of a <<ResourceInteraction>> between <<OrganisationalResource>>s

Asserts the phase of the enterprise that the architectural product describes.
Note that an architecture might cover a more extensive phase of an enterprise than an ArchitecturalProduct - i.e. each product may represent sub-phases of the enterprise covered by the architecture.
Asserts that an <<EnterprisePhase>> has, had or will have <<Capability>>
Asserts that a competence relates to an <<Function>> - i.e. any resource with that competence can carry out the function.
Where a function is only performed in context of a resource being part of another resource, this refers to that usage.
The estimated or actual end time for a project
The estimated or actual start date and time for a project.
If the activity is performed in context of the usage of the node, this property represents that usage.

Stereotype.name: CapabilityPackage
Stereotype.notes: This stereotype is used to tag root of the capability package. It can be recognized by artifact generators such as wsdl generator to identify relevant model entry points.

Stereotype.name: ConflictsWith
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Can be used to show which requirements are in conflict with one another.

Stereotype.name: ConstraintRequirement
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: A Constraint requirement are used to restrict how the developer can solve a problem. It provides a solution that the developer must use.Usually Constraint requirements are standards, legal obligations,...

Stereotype.name: DictionaryEntry
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: A word or a group of word having a particular meaning

Stereotype.name: FunctionalRequirement
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Functional Requirements define what the system/service/product/... can do. Usually they are used to specify what the acquirer wants to be able to do.

Stereotype.name: IsHomonymOf
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Describes the relationship between two identical terms who have different meanings

Stereotype.name: IsProjectionOf
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Describes the relationship between a general term and a specialized term

Stereotype.name: IsSynonymOf
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Describes the relationship between two terms having the same meaning

Stereotype.name: IsTranslationOf
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Describes the relationship between a term in different languages

Stereotype.name: NSOV-2
Stereotype.notes: This stereotype is used to tag root of the service description package.

Stereotype.name: NSV-11a
Stereotype.notes: This stereotype is used to tag logical group (common namespace) of data elements.

Stereotype.name: NSV-11b
Stereotype.notes: This stereotype is used to tag logical group (common namespace) of data elements.

Stereotype.name: OriginatesFrom
Stereotype.notes: CHRV: Is used to provide backward traceability to the source of a requirement

Stereotype.name: Principle
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: "Principles are general rules and guidelines, intended to be enduring and seldom amended, that inform and support the way in which an organization sets about fulfilling its mission." TOGAF chap 29

Stereotype.name: QualityRequirement
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Quality Requirements indicate how good, how reliable, how fast, the system/service/product/... has to be.

Stereotype.name: Realisation
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Specifies which requirement is implemented by which Capability/Process/Service/System/...

Stereotype.name: Requirement
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Untypified requirement used in CHRV diagrams when the modeler isn't certain yet what the requirements' type is.

Tag.name: FormalDefinition
Tag.default: [Wann?; Unter welche Bedingung] Muss Das System [-; <wem?> die Mglichkeit bieten; fhig sein] [Objekt & Ergnzung des Objekts] [Prozesswort]

Stereotype.name: RequirementAbstraction
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Is used to connect two Requirements of two different RAM Levels

Stereotype.name: SecurityRequirement
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Security Requirements are use to specify the security impacts and aspects of the system/service/product/...

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceDefinition
Stereotype.notes: This stereotype is used to tag a package as individual interface of a service.

Stereotype.name: ServiceInterfaceFault
Stereotype.notes: Interface level service fault.

Stereotype.notes: Operation level service fault.

Tag.name: S11/5 (Mo Fr 07:00 18:00 Uhr, ex-klusive Feiertage von Mo - Fr)

Stereotype.name: Specifies
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Defines the traceabiliy between a problem space NAF Element and a requirement precising it.

Stereotype.name: Supports
Stereotype.notes: CHAP: Shows which Principle/Requirements supports which principle

Stereotype.name: nillable
Stereotype.notes: Stereotype used to tag service parameters as nillable.

Stereotype.name: simpleType
Stereotype.notes: Stereotype to construct xsd simple data types using restrictions.
